00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:55.000
That's where you can just literally interact with Positron Assistant.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:59.000
Ask it questions about your data, your analyses, and it will get a response.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:01.000
You can chat that way.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:07.000
You can also leverage in-line code edits, which I'll demonstrate here in a little bit.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:12.000
Something that I'll talk a little bit more about in a second is that Positron Assistant

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:17.000
and pretty much all the AI features we have in Positron are model-agnostic,

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:19.000
meaning we're not going to force you to say,

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:22.000
hey, you need to use ChatTPT or you have to use Gemini.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:26.000
Chances are your team may only approve certain tools.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:29.000
We want to make sure that you can bring those tools to Positron and use them.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:32.000
Positron is not in the business of creating our own LLMs.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:37.000
We just want to make sure you can use the LLMs that you can use in Positron right out of the box.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:43.000
Lastly, Positron and Positron Assistant are designed for data science.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:48.000
The way that Positron Assistant does this is pretty cool, and it's also a little creepy.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:54.000
Here I have the Positron IDE, and I put purposely some very creepy eyes on it.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:12:00.000
When you interact with Positron Assistant, it can actually see your Positron environment.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:04.000
It can know that, hey, you have this Quarto document open,

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:07.000
or, hey, you have some variables stored in memory.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:10.000
I can see the plots that you've created.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:15.000
I also know what code you're in in your console and what error messages or output that you got.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:21.000
That way, when you make suggestions or questions to Positron Assistant,

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:26.000
typically the suggestions you get and the responses just tend to work immediately,

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:30.000
because it automatically knows everything it needs to know about your environment.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:34.000
I'm going to hopefully demonstrate that functionality here in a second.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:37.000
That's one way to interact with Positron Assistant.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:41.000
Again, using this little chat box in the bottom left.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:45.000
There is another way. This is known as inline code suggestions.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:51.000
If you have a Shiny application open or a Quarto document or a Python script or a FastAPI,

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:56.000
you can typically hit Command-I if you're on Mac or Control-I if you're on a Windows machine.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:03.000
You can open up this little chat assistant window where you can make edits directly to your source code that way.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:07.000
Again, we'll be demonstrating that here in a second.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:11.000
This is going back to that mentality of Positron.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:14.000
Again, we are not in the model creation space.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:19.000
We just want to make sure that you can bring your own models into Positron and Positron Assistant.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:24.000
Currently right now, Anthropics is really just the main model that we support,

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.000
and we are actively testing out other models.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:32.000
As Positron Assistant continues to evolve, we hope to support additional models in the future.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:37.000
Positron Assistant is one tool that we're going to talk about in this short demo.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:40.000
There's another one, and this is called DataBot.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:43.000
I'm curious. Anybody here try out DataBot?

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:46.000
Okay, we've got a few hands. That's cool.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
The vast majority have not. That's expected.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:51.000
It's a really new tool. It's a very exciting tool.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:55.000
Honestly, it's probably one of the more fun tools that I've ever interacted with.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:59.000
Unlike Positron Assistant that's built into Positron,

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:01.000
DataBot is actually an extension.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:06.000
If you're a VS Code user, you'll know that there's a very rich library of extensions you can import

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:10.000
into your Positron session to customize your development space.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:14.000
DataBot is, in fact, an extension.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:17.000
The way that DataBot works is pretty cool.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:21.000
We've coined this internally, called the WHERE loop.

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:25.000
It's really designed for exploratory data analysis.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:27.000
You get a brand new data set thrown at you,

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:30.000
and typically the first thing you want to do is just understand what that data is,

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:33.000
what it's telling you, maybe extract some insights.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:36.000
That's where DataBot comes into play.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.000
If you have a new data set, you can open up DataBot,

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:41.000
and you can just say, hey, DataBot, tell me about this data.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:44.000
What it's going to do is kick off this WHERE loop.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:48.000
The first thing you'll do is write R or Python code on your behalf,

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:50.000
again, with your approval.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:55.000
This is also something that, again, the way we interact with these LLMs is all code-based,

00:14:55.000 --> 00:15:00.000
because we know that code is the most auditable way to interact with LLMs.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:03.000
DataBot's going to start writing some R or Python code,

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:05.000
and it will execute it immediately.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:08.000
It'll actually analyze those results,

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:11.000
and then regroup and offer some additional suggestions.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:13.000
Then you can give it the next instruction,

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:16.000
and this WHERE loop will just go around and around and around in circles

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:22.000
until you are confident you know everything you need to know about this data set.

